They do need to review the act; to save a small bait fish in the delta, that has no impact to the food chain, created the """"dust bowl"""" that is now California's Central Valley; thousands of jobs lost, billions of dollars lost, greater erosion of top soil, greater deterioration of the aquifer (the drought) without water from the aqueducts; there has to be common sense balance between the environment, economics, and people. I read the article it doesn't say they are eliminating the endangered species act; it talks about reviewing it and making it more balanced. I've worked on projects that were delayed for years, cost millions of dollars in overruns, because the day the EPA inspector came out inspect the construction site he found """"fairy shrimp"""", shrimp that only occur when it rains, live in puddles, then die when the puddle dries up. If he had inspected on a sunny day - no shrimp, and the project would have started on time. The rules do have to be reviewed.
